{"id":"d=origam-topic-4409//p=0b87bf154e2c46d7943b7a36c34f09e3","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4409"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["c89a408d6f8f4b9fb2bd802f104a9b13"],"__file_part":["4c3e12f5599d4f48ba7a0cff6d83fbf1"],"__part_n":["1"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["4409"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-rename-database-entities-and-fields/4409"],"title":["How to rename database entities and fields"],"imagesFound":["12"],"imagesDescribed":["12"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/d/d61bdc8d10ebc460c3de125d65c72306f7d4e4be.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/ae97b5dde46b922273bc2a189cb4023294218ebb.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/110b87b6e66bb04c14467edc53663deebc244c31.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/cc5e55121cd1f561a60d1a01f39bf9e10d4d7d33.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/ae2217c8be95110874f0cb4ec8d4a4d372a18a5e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/cd8256fea1faa57e44eca6b88732aed4c6d6e6db.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/bb8552d09eee418969e3ac0c04d2393502ef118f.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/9/95c31d2c99f8339b0b2c82d458aef235a242c944.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/3b502267ae2c04c59a64c3761d32b909ec5374f5.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/12f75cff62f78c6e59c301c765313cec8f173e72.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/2/2ea702a15e1c7585be388665443a56bc23627740.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5f11e4b138365cc1e635b9dd4a5a6a0678544731.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" Model Browser is technically the simplest part of the process \u2014 just click the name and change it. \n In this example, we rename the entity  Status  to  TaskStatus  and the field  Task.refStatusId  to  Task.refTaskStatusId . \n Immediately after performing such a change, the application becomes inconsistent. If you attempt to open a form related to the renamed entity in the client application, you will encounter an error: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/cc5e55121cd1f561a60d1a01f39bf9e10d4d7d33.png]\nDescription: The image displays an error message from a software environment, indicating a failure in processing a database operation. The text shows an error code and description: \u0022Error Number: 208, State: 1, Class: 16\u0022, followed by the label \u0022fail!\u0022 highlighted in red. The message further details: \u0022Origam.Server.Middleware.OrigamErrorHandlingMiddleware[0] Invalid object name \u0027TaskStatus\u0027.\u0022 The final line reiterates the exception type: \u0022Origam.DA.DatabaseTableNotFoundException: Invalid object name \u0027TaskStatus\u0027.\u0022 This context suggests that the system encountered a problem when attempting to access a database table that does not exist or is improperly named.\n\n\n  \n A similar situation occurs when renaming a field: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/ae2217c8be95110874f0cb4ec8d4a4d372a18a5e.png]\nDescription: A modal error dialog is displayed at the top of the interface, indicated by a red warning icon. The title reads \u0022Error\u0022 and the message states: \u0022Error loading data from table \u0027Task\u0027 into entity \u0027Task\u0027. Message: Invalid column name \u0027refTaskStatusId\u0027. Exception was encountered while updating data. For more information see Details.\u0022 Below the message, there is an \u0027OK\u0027 button in a blue rectangular shape. The purpose of this dialog is to inform the user of a data loading issue related to a specified column in a database.\n\n\n  \n Let\u2019s fix this step by step. \n   Database object name changes \n The first issue to resolve is the database. Referencing a non-existing table or column is a critical problem. \n In principle, you have two options \u2014 perform the change manually or use a deployment script. The recommended approach is clear, but for testing purposes you may also try the manual method. \n   Manual procedure \n Below is an example SQL script for renaming a table in MS SQL Server. You can execute it directly in the database query tool: \n  USE [taskman];\nGO\nEXEC sp_rename \u0027dbo.Status\u0027, \u0027TaskStatus\u0027;\nGO\n  \n Similarly, to rename a database column: \n  USE [taskman];\nGO\nEXEC sp_rename \n    \u0027dbo.Task.refStatusId\u0027, \n    \u0027refTaskStatusId\u0027, \n    \u0027COLUMN\u0027;\nGO\n  \n   Using deployment scripts \n To ensure that the change is propagated to all database instances associated with the application model, you should create a new  Service Command Update Activity : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/cd8256fea1faa57e44eca6b88732aed4c6d6e6db.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a user interface, likely part of a software application for managing update activities within a system. The visible UI text includes the version indicators \u00221.0.0\u0022 and \u00222.0.0,\u0022 along with a hierarchical list of activities. The listed items are \u0022File Restore Update Activity,\u0022 highlighted as the first item, and \u0022Service Command Update Activity,\u0022 which is selected. Additional options include a button labeled \u0022New,\u0022 a button for \u0022New Group,\u0022 and a \u0022Repeat New\u0022 option. The context suggests this interface is part of a project management or database handling tool aimed at managing different update activities efficiently.\n\n\n  \n When using a deployment script within the model, you do not need the  USE  or  GO  commands: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/bb8552d09eee418969e3ac0c04d2393502ef118f.png]\nDescription: Service Command Update Activity interface displaying fields for Name, Order, Service, Platform, and Command. The Name field contains \u002200130_Rename_Status_to_TaskStatus\u0022, the Order is set to \u0022130\u0022, the Service is labeled \u0022DataService\u0022, and the Platform indicates \u0022MsSql\u0022. The Command section includes the SQL statement: \u0022EXEC sp_rename \u0027dbo.Status\u0027, \u0027TaskStatus\u0027;\u0022, indicating the purpose of renaming a database column from \u0022Status\u0022 to \u0022TaskStatus\u0022.\n\n\n  \n Be sure to provide the script with a meaningful name. ","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:58:40"},"vector":[-0.009041145,-0.009076493,-0.08021542,0.022128437,-0.01131852,-0.034024175,0.01985418,0.0047149844,-0.017476408,0.016639667,-0.012131371,-0.03424994,0.010991823,0.021683807,0.007225221,-0.023228694,0.012921145,0.020666346,0.01736933,0.043668557,-0.014751997,0.008452615,0.032326575,-0.010042334,-0.018076852,0.013496607,-0.0070718783,-0.033928275,0.0121050095,0.0024627033,0.02682209,-0.075264625,-0.02676986,-0.07120597,-0.024075389,0.007963021,0.02199344,0.0008128797,-0.042152423,0.011109557,-0.0070764143,-0.00969633,-0.01650306,-0.021651525,0.040502302,-0.01799833,-0.011397224,-0.0016339938,0.029204132,-0.034467604,-0.03616351,-0.009574839,0.034672163,-0.009181028,0.04696779,0.029921575,-0.04433232,-0.0005367353,-0.07958741,0.0037729405,-0.03618499,-0.014743618,-0.014183963,-0.02431961,-0.020123485,0.04557424,0.024856063,-0.01857986,-0.0036350782,-0.079907954,0.016254762,0.03814454,-0.07272002,-0.041597873,-0.048150968,0.025204988,0.038800776,0.006096986,0.001574177,-0.023353918,-0.008802098,0.026738118,-0.04381712,-0.021678893,-0.013376594,0.021356575,-0.008986372,0.023188297,0.009419443,0.020546885,0.015973525,-0.02447041,0.050012004,-0.0013324635,-0.02551797,-0.013516077,0.0041938894,0.0